vectorData.altText: 5. The tearing of meningeal arteries causes an intracranial accumulation of blood called an _________________ _________________.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

That’s right! Meningeal arteries lie between the periosteal layer of the dura and the inner table of the cranial bones. When these vessels rupture, the periosteum is torn from the bony surfaces, causing an epidural hematoma.

The meningeal arteries are located between the inner surface of the skull bone and the periosteal layer of dura. The largest meningeal artery is the middle meningeal artery, a branch of the external carotid artery that passes into the cranial cavity through the foramen spinosum. The position of the middle meningeal artery between the inner surface of the skull bone and the periosteal layer of dura has clinical significance in traumatic injuries to the skull.

The skull is thinnest and most fragile at the pterion, where four cranial bones come together: the frontal, parietal, temporal and sphenoid bones. A branch of the middle meningeal artery crosses the pterion, where skull fractures are common. Tearing of the middle meningeal artery can cause an extradural (epidural) hematoma.
